Growing up I had developed a weird thick alien skin due to living in a home full of violence, as well as a world that was full to the brim with bullshit. I found humor in things that people didn't notice, or that weren't funny at all. This is me, in 1985, looking at some jagoff trying to get me to take the damn school photo, clearly saying, "Fuck this guy". I was in a city that sucked, at a school that was trying to get me to learn shit that I would have to spend the rest of my life unlearning, and I had a helmet of a haircut that would later on become some ironic statement related to punk. And yes, I am wearing an Izod shirt, the clothing of many assholes. My dad wore that shit most of his life and my mom got me a disgusting Easter yellow colored shirt to wear for this photo opt. You can scroll back through all my photos and see the one taken after this year, where I had a flattop and a Per Welinder shirt on. I wanted to shave my head, as well as my eyebrows, but my mom would not let me, so I decided I'd try to look like Jack Diddley from the 1983 film Suburbia. My dad was murdered around that time and all hell broke loose in my life. The year after the flattop school photo was a weird razored mop haircut, where I was finally looking like a perfect piece of shit. Then it was just downhill haircuts and fashion till my mom kicked me out of the house. Bingo! Here's to looking like a decent kid for the last time in one's life.

Check out the New York premiere for the film “Don’t Fall In Love With Yourself” @dontfallinlovewithyourselfdoc about Justin Pearson’s label Three One G @threeoneg!

After the film, stay for a Q&A with Justin Pearson and director Jon Nix @jonnixfilm, followed by live performances with Three One G artists Netherlands @nethrock and Planet B @planetbband.

Presented by Saint Vitus @saintvitusbar.

Don’t Fall in Love With Yourself is a documentary that explores the life of musician and artist, Justin Pearson. From childhood tragedy and his roots in the San Diego punk scene, to his appearance on Jerry Springer. An in-depth look at a career made out of blood, sweat and spit.

Much of the B-roll has been sourced from dozens of VHS & Mini-DV tapes recorded over the past three decades. Controversial and never-before-seen footage of one of the most interesting and unique musical movements is recent memory.

The film’s interviews include Justin Pearson, Dave Lombardo @davelombardo, Eric Paul @ericpaulpvd, Gabe Serbian @gabeserbian, Bobby Bray @bobby_bray, Travis Ryan @travisryancattledecap, Jeremy Bolm @jeremyxbolm, Jon Syverson @jonathan_syverson, Molly Neuman @mollydneuman, Becky DiGiglio @yourethenight and more.

Don't Fall In Love With Yourself @dontfallinlovewithyourselfdoc will be screening in Cleveland, OH on April 2nd and Akron, OH on the 4th. There is a lot to unpack with something like this. First off, it is weird to have a film based on the stuff I am and have been part of. I'm grateful that anyone cared to make the film, then screen it, and then hopefully watch it. The best parts of the film are with Gabe Serbian @gabeserbian, who in retrospect I think the film should have been about. I miss that guy every day. Also, my mother is hilarious in it, especially when I get her to wear The Locust @the_locust_official mask. She is so cool. 

With these screenings, I am so grateful to the TurnStyle @turnstylefilms crew and Earthquaker Devices @earthquakerdev for sorting things out and having myself, and Luke Henshaw @mr_henshaw, who scored a portion of the film, come out for the screening's Q&A segments. 

I hope some of you can make it, and I look forward to the film being officially released on streaming services, on Blu Ray, and also the film's score which is getting a proper release. If anyone has questions about the details of all of this, or future screenings, please reach out to TurnStyle as I'm just the jerk in the film.

I recently visited my soon to turn 94 year old Grandmother in Carlinville, IL. Even though we have very little in common as far as our interests, she is my family and helped raise me as a child. Some of her childhood stories she shared with me were mind blowing. I tried to wrap my head around the small town she lived in (and is once again living in), hearing stories of growing up in poverty in a much different time, and her take on current life in this drastically different world. At the assisted living home she currently resides at, one of the employees there found out I play in a band and got it in her head that I'm a big deal. She had my grandmother give her my autograph, which was weird, and amusing, as I am 100% certain the person would be so confused by what I do musically. I'm looking forward to my extremely mentally sharp Grandmother turning 100, as it gives me hope that my mind and body may make it that far, assuming humans don't completely destroy the planet before I get there.

PLANET B @planetbband - Fiction Prediction LP

Justin Pearson @justinpearson31g, Luke Henshaw @mr_henshaw, Kevin Avery @definitelydude and Scott Osment @scottosment formed Planet B with the shared purpose of creating music subversive in sound and sobering in message. Their music lays somewhere just out of reach of genre, with aesthetics rooted in hip hop, hardcore punk, turntablism, and 70s-80s horror movie scores. It is catchy, heavily percussive, and eerie all at once. The band’s first self-titled LP showcased the band collaborating with artists such as Kool Keith @officialkoolkeith, Nick Zinner @little_vampire, Martin Atkins @flowersfightforsunshine, K. Joseph Karam @k.joseph.karam, and Sonny Kay @sonny_kay. The band has also released splits with electronic punk duo ADULT. @adultperiod and turntablist collective Invisibl Skratch Piklz @ispiklz. The band also formed an offshoot  with The Satanic Temple @thesatanictemple co-founder and spokesperson, Lucien Greaves; this project is called Satanic Planet @satanicplanetofficial. Fiction Prediction sees a similar array of collaborators.

Planet B’s second LP has been a long time in the making. Obviously, over this span of time, there has been an almost unimaginable amount of surreality and insanity to pull from when creating the band’s unique hip-hop-punk-meets-sci-fi-horror-movie sonic aesthetic. As always, the sound is as confrontational as it is catchy, the lyrics scathing and the beats bizarre. Earworms abound. As with the band’s first release, there are a host of guest collaborations on the various tracks, from Josie Cotton @josiecottonofficial to David Scott Stone @sirdss, D-Styles @djdstyles, and more. Perhaps most personally meaningful are the instrumental contributions from Gabe Serbian @gabeserbian and Eric Livingston @firstchurchofthevoid, both family to the band, who have each passed on from this dimension and back to whatever radical planet they came from since the creation of the album.

In the book, How To Lose Friends and Irritate People, Justin Pearson @justinpearson31g reveals his misadventures with two DJ duos borrowing him as a frontman, lending some “punk” street cred to their music. Known for being part of bands like The Locust, All Leather, and Retox, as well as the owner of Three One G Records, Justin has paved the way for bizarre, abrasive and political music, while pushing the envelope of what is expected or what can be done in a band. The Bloody Beetroots and Designer Drugs approached him to sing on their albums, and what came out of those two experiences is both pathetic and hilarious. From being forced to lip sync at Australian festivals in front of thousands, to being lost in the woods somewhere in Pennsylvania at a music video shoot gone wrong, Justin questions not only the DJ’s motives, but his own as well. Embracing actual musical instrumentation instead of laptop playlists, Justin trudges through the murky waters of musical capitalism.

How To Lose Friends and Irritate People is comprised of two stories, “Now I Will Make a Sound For You to Hear, A Sound Without My Mouth” and “A Sucker is Born Every Minute”, originally separately bound in each own book, as well as a flexi record in each book featuring All Leather “We Eat Gauche Caviar” and Ill Saint M “A Pig’s Orphan” (featuring Justin Pearson). All parts bound together as one, creating more than just a book, but a collectors item, artifact, and maybe even an all around “fuck you” to Kindles and digital downloads. The book has since been reprinted as one novella, featuring only one of the Flexi postcard records as part of the packaging.
